Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Nivelles, Brabant wallon, Belgique":"Nivelles, Walloon Brabant, Belgium","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Saint","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Center","meanings":["English and Scottish (Aberdeenshire): metonymic occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>ceinture</i>, <i>seinture</i> ‘girdle’, denoting someone who made or sold girdles, or perhaps a nickname for someone who wore a distinctive girdle.","English: variant of   Senter   1.","Americanized form of German   Zehnder   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Sant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Krishan, Anagha, Anjali, Arvind, Deepak, Milind, Nilima, Ravindra, Sanjeev, Sanjiv, Vasudev.","English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Saint  .","Italian (northeastern): variant of   Santo  ."]},{"name":"Sante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Luc, Camille, Lucien.  Spanish Alejandro, Anselmo, Carlos, Emilio, Jesusa, Jorge.","French (also <b>Santé</b>): probably a nickname for a healthy person, from French <i>santé</i> ‘good health’.","Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Spanish (southwestern): habitational name from one of several places called Sante, in Galicia, Portugal, and Asturias, from a Visigothic personal name. This surname is also found in the Philippines."]}]},{"name":"Gand","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Gain  .","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Wano</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>wan</i> ‘hope, expectation’. Compare   Degan   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Gain","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname for a cunning person, from <i>Engaine</i>, which is based on Old French <i>engaigne</i> ‘ingenuity, cunning, trickery’.","English: habitiational name from any of various places called after the <i>Engain</i> family, including Colne Engaine and Gaynes Park (Essex), d'Engaine's Farm (Cambridgeshire), and Aston Ingham (Hereford). <i>Engaine</i> (see 1 above) was the name of a powerful Norman family with lands in several counties. The original form of the surname has since died out, surviving as <i>Gain</i> and its variants. There has also been considerable confusion with   Ingham  .","French: nickname from a noun derivative of Old French <i>gaainier</i> ‘to obtain, gain, win’."]}]},{"name":"Baudouin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Baldwin</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Baudouin Guillaume de Saint Omer-de Gand was born in 1030, in Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Rabel de SAINT-OMER, was 28 and his mother, Ghislaine de GAND, was 22. He married Mahaut de CRÉQUY in 1049. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1097, in his hometown, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1030–1097":"1030–1097","1027–1080":"1027–1080","0995–1044":"0995–1044","1052–1072":"1052–1072","1050–Male":"1050–Surnud","1002–Male":"1002–Surnud","1008–1059":"1008–1059","1080":"1080","1044":"1044","1097":"1097","1030":"1030","1052":"1052","1050":"1050","1072":"1072","1008":"1008","1049":"1049","0995":"0995","1027":"1027","1059":"1059","1002":"1002","16 novembre 1044":"16. november 1044","Gand, Flandre-Orientale, Belgique":"Gent, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia","Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Saint-Omer, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Pran